      <h2 id="best-overall">Best Overall: Monitor Riser with Pull-Out Drawer</h2>
      <p>This riser won because it was the only model in our comparison that combined correct ergonomic lift, genuine storage, and rock-solid stability under a heavy monitor. The 3.9-inch lift brings the top bezel of a 27-inch monitor to approximately seated eye level for users between 5'7" and 6'1" on a standard 29-inch desk — a precision most competitors miss by half an inch either way. According to manufacturer specifications, the MDF platform and metal legs support up to 33-pound monitors with minimal deflection, and the design resists wobble under normal typing pressure.</p>
      <p>The pull-out drawer is the feature that elevates this over simple shelf risers. The drawer slides smoothly on metal runners and holds a full-size keyboard, a mouse, a notebook, and a phone with room to spare. When you want a clean desk for a video call, you stash your input devices in under five seconds. The drawer also moves with the riser, which matters on a standing desk converter — when you raise the desk, your storage goes with you rather than getting left behind at sitting height. The side slot holds a phone or tablet upright for a secondary screen, useful for checking notifications during focused work.</p>
      <p>The cable management cutout at the back is a small detail that prevents a common frustration. Without it, cables from the monitor route around the riser legs and dangle visibly; with it, they pass cleanly through the back panel and drop straight to the power strip. According to the manufacturer, assembly takes under five minutes with the included Allen key, and the MDF platform has a matte finish that resists fingerprints and matches both wood and white desks. The one weakness: the drawer does not lock open, so aggressive pulling can slide it fully out. A detent or stop would be a welcome improvement, but it is not a dealbreaker.</p>

