      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: Simple Bamboo Monitor Shelf</h2>
      <p>If you do not need storage and want to spend under $20, the bamboo monitor shelf is the value pick. It is a single slab of bamboo with four metal legs, providing a 3.5-inch lift that is close to ergonomic for most users. The bamboo looks genuinely good on wood desks — better than the MDF alternative — and the platform is large enough for a 27-inch monitor with the stand on top. According to manufacturer specifications, the design supports up to 20-pound monitors without noticeable wobble, and assembly is simply screwing in four legs.</p>
      <p>The tradeoffs are the absence of storage and cable management. There is no drawer, no side slot, and no cable cutout, so cables route around the legs visibly and your keyboard stays on the desk surface. The 3.5-inch lift is slightly less than the 3.9-inch drawer riser, which may leave shorter monitors half an inch below ideal eye level. For minimalists with large desks who only need the ergonomic lift and like the bamboo aesthetic, this is excellent value. For anyone who wants to declutter, the drawer riser is worth the extra $16.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>The first measurement to take is the lift you actually need. Sit at your desk with good posture and look straight ahead. Note where your eye line falls on the monitor — if it is above the top bezel, you need a riser; if it is below the top third of the screen, you do not. Measure from the desk surface to your seated eye level, subtract the monitor's height from base to top bezel, and the remainder is your target lift. Most people land between 3.5 and 4.5 inches. Buying a riser that is too tall is as bad as none at all — you will end up looking up, which strains the neck differently but equally.</p>
      <p>Material choice determines both stability and aesthetics. MDF with metal legs is the most rigid and supports the heaviest monitors — rated for up to 33 pounds. Solid bamboo is nearly as rigid and looks better on wood desks, but the platform thickness limits weight capacity. Plastic risers are light and cheap but flex under heavy monitors and can crack over time; they are not recommended for anything over 15 pounds. If you have a heavy all-in-one like an iMac or a large ultrawide, MDF or metal is the safe choice.</p>
      <p>Finally, decide whether storage matters for your setup. If your desk is large and uncluttered, a simple shelf riser is cheaper and equally stable. If your desk is small or you want a clean surface for video calls, a drawer riser converts the space under your monitor into functional storage that you will actually use daily. The cable cutout is a feature worth specifically checking for — without it, your monitor cables will route around the riser legs and look messy, undermining the clean aesthetic that a riser is supposed to provide. Combine a drawer riser with our recommended laptop stand and cable management box, and you can build a fully professional workstation for under $90 total.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>How high should a monitor riser lift my screen?</summary>
          <p>The top bezel of your monitor should sit at or just below eye level when you sit with good posture. For most people on a standard 29-inch desk with a 24-27 inch monitor, that means a 3.5 to 4 inch lift. Measure from your desk surface to your seated eye level, subtract the monitor's own height, and that is the lift you need.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Can a monitor riser support a 34-inch ultrawide monitor?</summary>
          <p>Most MDF and metal risers rated for 30+ lbs can support an ultrawide, but check the platform depth. A 34-inch ultrawide needs a riser at least 9 inches deep to support the stand base without tipping. Avoid plastic risers for monitors over 20 lbs — they flex and crack over time under sustained load.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Is a monitor riser with a drawer worth it versus a simple shelf?</summary>
          <p>If your desk is cluttered, yes. The drawer converts the dead space under your monitor into usable storage for keyboard, mouse, and notebooks, which is especially valuable on small desks. If you have a large desk with ample storage, a simple shelf riser is cheaper and equally stable.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

